<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">What Is a Grade Calculator?</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Let's be real: nobody wants to dig through a syllabus with a calculator in one hand and a coffee in the other just to figure out where their grade stands. A grade calculator does the heavy lifting for you. You punch in your scores, tell it how much each assignment counts, and it tells you your grade. That's it.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Students use these things for all sorts of reasons. Maybe you want to check where you stand halfway through the semester. Maybe you need to know exactly what you have to get on the final to keep your scholarship. Or maybe you just want to see if that B+ on your last essay helped or hurt your average.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The Calcluster Grade Calculator puts four handy tools on one page: a Weighted Grade Calculator, a GPA Calculator, a What-If Predictor, and a Letter Grade Converter. They're all free, totally private, and work just as well on your phone as they do on a laptop.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A grade calculator is a free online tool that figures out your academic grade by taking each assignment score, multiplying it by how much that assignment is worth, adding everything up, and turning the final number into a letter grade. Students use a grade calculator to check their standing during the semester, find out what score they need on a final exam to hit a target grade, compute their GPA across several courses, and convert percentage scores to letter grades on the spot.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You've been there. You just got an exam back, and now you're staring at the ceiling thinking, "Okay&hellip; so what's my grade <strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">actually</strong> at?" That's where a grade calculator comes in. Instead of pulling out your syllabus, hunting down percentages, and doing a bunch of multiplication, you just type a few numbers and click a button.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">But a good grade calculator does more than just average stuff out. The really useful part is the planning. You should be able to say, "Here's where I am right now. Here's where I want to be. Tell me what I need for the rest of my work to get there." That's what students really care about &mdash; especially when finals are around the corner and every point feels like it matters.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This tool does exactly that. It works for a 6th grader trying to keep up with homework just as well as it works for a college senior calculating what she needs on her last final to keep her financial aid. The numbers change, but the process is the same: put in your info, get a clear answer.</p>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How to Use the Grade Calculator (Step-by-Step)</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You'll see four tabs across the top. Each one does something different. You don't need all four &mdash; just click the one that matches what you're trying to figure out.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">How to Use the Weighted Grade Calculator (Tab 1)</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Use this tab when your class has weighted categories &mdash; homework worth 20%, tests 50%, quizzes 30%&hellip; that kind of setup.</p>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Step 1:</strong> Click the green "+ Add Category" button to make a row for each part of your class. Typical ones: Homework, Quizzes, Midterm, Final Exam, Projects, Lab Reports &mdash; whatever is on your syllabus.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Step 2:</strong> Fill in the three boxes for each row. The Category Name is just for you (optional). Score (%) is the grade you got in that category. Weight (%) is how much it counts toward your final grade &mdash; check your syllabus for this.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Step 3:</strong> Watch the weight badge near the top. It adds up your weights as you go and turns green when they hit exactly 100%, showing "Perfect!" That's your signal that everything is set up right. If the weights don't add up to 100, the calculator will warn you.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Step 4:</strong> Click "Calculate Grade." Your overall grade shows up as a percentage with the letter grade right below it.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Step 5:</strong> Made a mistake? Hit Reset and start over.</li>
</ol>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">One quick note: if you're in the middle of the semester and some categories don't have grades yet, just leave those rows out. The calculator works fine with whatever is already graded.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">How to Use the GPA Calculator (Tab 2)</h3>
