<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This comes in handy more often than you'd think &mdash; especially when a teacher posts a letter grade but your gradebook tracks everything as percentages.</p>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Will My Grade Go Up or Down? How to Check</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A lot of students come to a grade calculator after getting one score back and wanting to know: did that help me or hurt me? The answer isn't just about whether the score was good or bad &mdash; it depends on how much that assignment is worth.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Will My Grade Go Up Calculator</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">If the score you just got is higher than your current average, yes &mdash; your grade goes up. But <strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">how much</strong> depends almost entirely on the weight. A 98% on a tiny homework assignment barely moves the needle. A 98% on a final worth 40% of your grade moves it a ton.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">To see the exact impact, go to the Weighted Grade tab, enter all your existing categories plus the new score as a new row, and run the calculation. Compare that result to what your grade was before &mdash; the difference is your increase.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Will My Grade Drop Calculator</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Same logic applies when a score comes in lower than your average. A 55% on a quiz worth 5% stings a little. A 55% on a final worth 40% can be genuinely damaging. The weight determines the actual damage.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">To check the drop, add the new score into your Weighted Grade tab with its correct weight and see how your overall percentage changes.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Will I Pass Grade Calculator</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">If passing is genuinely on the line, go to the What-If tab. Enter your current grade, the percentage of the course graded so far, and set your target to 60% (the most common US passing threshold). The result tells you exactly what you need on remaining work to pass. If that number is realistic, you have a path. If it comes back above 100%, it's time to talk to your teacher.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">How Much Will My Grade Go Up Calculator</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The most accurate way: use the Weighted Grade tab before and after adding a new score. Run it without the new score, write down the result, then add the new row and run it again. The difference is exactly how much your grade moved.</p>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How Grade Calculations Actually Work: The Math Behind the Tool</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">If you've ever wondered what's actually happening when the calculator spits out a number, here's the math. It's simpler than it looks.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">The Weighted Average Formula</h3>
<div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
  Final Grade (%) = Total of all (Score &times; Weight) &divide; Total Weight
</div>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">In plain English: take each category, multiply the score by the weight (as a decimal, so 30% becomes 0.30), add up all those products, and divide by the sum of the weights. If your weights add up to 100 &mdash; which they should &mdash; that last step is just dividing by 100.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">A Worked Example</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Say your course looks like this:</p>
<div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
    <li>Homework: 95%, worth 20% &rarr; 95 &times; 0.20 = 19.0</li>
    <li>Quizzes: 82%, worth 30% &rarr; 82 &times; 0.30 = 24.6</li>
    <li>Midterm: 74%, worth 20% &rarr; 74 &times; 0.20 = 14.8</li>
    <li>Final Exam: 88%, worth 30% &rarr; 88 &times; 0.30 = 26.4</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Add those up: 19.0 + 24.6 + 14.8 + 26.4 = 84.8% &mdash; that's a B.</p>
</div>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">How to Compute It by Hand</h3>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
  <li>Write down each category with its score and weight.</li>
  <li>Turn the weight into a decimal (20% = 0.20).</li>
  <li>Multiply the score by the decimal weight.</li>
  <li>Add all those products together.</li>
  <li>That sum is your grade percentage.</li>
  <li>Look it up in the grade scale to get your letter grade.</li>
</ol>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Most errors happen at step 2 &mdash; people forget to convert the percentage to a decimal. The calculator does this automatically.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">The What-If Formula</h3>
<div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
  Required Score = (Target Grade &minus; Current Grade &times; Weight Completed) &divide; Weight Remaining<br />
  Weight Remaining = 100 &minus; Weight Completed
</div>
<div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Example: You have 85%, 70% of the course is done, and you want a 90%.</p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">(90 &minus; 85 &times; 0.70) &divide; 0.30 = (90 &minus; 59.5) &divide; 0.30 = 30.5 &divide; 0.30 = 101.7%</p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-0">That number above 100% tells you a 90% is impossible &mdash; even a perfect score wouldn't get you there.</p>
</div>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">The GPA Formula</h3>
<div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
  GPA = Total of (Grade Points &times; Credits) &divide; Total Credits
</div>
<div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">On a 4.0 scale: A=4.0, B=3.0, C=2.0, D=1.0, F=0.0.</p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-0">Two 3-credit courses: one A and one C. (4.0&times;3 + 2.0&times;3) &divide; 6 = 18 &divide; 6 = 3.0 GPA.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Letter Grade Scale and GPA Reference</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This is the standard US scale. Your school might define cutoffs slightly differently.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Standard Scale (No Plus/Minus)</h3>
<ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">A: 90–100% (4.0)</strong> &mdash; Excellent</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">B: 80–89% (3.0)</strong> &mdash; Above average</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">C: 70–79% (2.0)</strong> &mdash; Satisfactory</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">D: 60–69% (1.0)</strong> &mdash; Below average, but passing</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">F: Below 60% (0.0)</strong> &mdash; Failing</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Plus/Minus Scale</h3>
<ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">A+: 97–100% (4.0 or 4.3 at some schools)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">A: 93–96% (4.0)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">A&minus;: 90–92% (3.7)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">B+: 87–89% (3.3)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">B: 83–86% (3.0)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">B&minus;: 80–82% (2.7)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">C+: 77–79% (2.3)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">C: 73–76% (2.0)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">C&minus;: 70–72% (1.7)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">D+: 67–69% (1.3)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">D: 63–66% (1.0)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">D&minus;: 60–62% (0.7)</strong></li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">F: Below 60% (0.0)</strong></li>
</ul>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">One note on A+: some schools treat it as 4.0 (same as a regular A), others use a 4.3 scale. The GPA tab lets you choose.</p>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Grade Calculator for Different Grade Levels</h2>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Middle School (6th, 7th, 8th Grade)</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Most middle school classes don't use complicated weighted categories. Many teachers just track total points. If that's your situation, you can still use the Weighted Grade tab &mdash; just give every row the same weight. Ten assignments? Give each 10%. The math works fine.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The What-If tab is underused by middle schoolers, but it's really helpful heading into end-of-year exams. Sitting at 72% and wondering if you can pull a B? Plug your numbers in and find out.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">High School</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">High school is where weighted grades become the norm. Most courses break grades into categories &mdash; classwork, tests, quizzes, midterm, final &mdash; each with different percentages. That makes the Weighted Grade tab the most important one.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">High schoolers should also use the GPA tab regularly. Colleges look at your cumulative GPA, not just individual grades. Tracking it yourself gives you early warning if something slips.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">College</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">College courses often have more complex grading. Professors sometimes weight individual assignments differently. The syllabus has the breakdown &mdash; the Weighted Grade tab is where you enter it.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The GPA tab is critical in college because your GPA affects academic standing, scholarships, honors programs, and grad school applications. Keeping a live estimate gives you time to adjust if a semester isn't going well.</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Teachers</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Teachers use grade calculators differently. Instead of checking their own grades, they use the Weighted Grade tab to verify their grading structure before sharing it with a class. You can enter planned category weights &mdash; Homework 20%, Quizzes 20%, Tests 40%, Final 20% &mdash; and confirm they add up to 100%. You can also model sample scores to see how grades shake out.</p>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Where to Find a Grade Calculator</h2>

