<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Why Your Calculated Grade Might Not Match the Gradebook</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This is a super common question. You run your numbers, get 84.7%, and the school's system says 83.2%. What gives?</p>
<ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Rounding policies</strong> are the usual culprit. Some teachers round each assignment before averaging. Others carry decimals through and only round at the end. Both are fine &mdash; they just give slightly different numbers. If you ever need to check how a score shift affects a percentage, our <a href="/tools/percent-increase/" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">Percent Increase Calculator</a> can help.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Dropped scores</strong> also cause mismatches. If your class drops the lowest quiz grade, you need to remove it from your calculation too.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Extra credit</strong> is tricky. Some teachers let it push a category above 100%. Others cap it. Ask your teacher how it works.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Missing assignments</strong> matter. Until a teacher enters a zero, some gradebooks pretend those assignments don't exist &mdash; artificially inflating your grade. When those zeroes hit, your grade drops. That's why tracking it yourself helps.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Curves and regrades</strong> also throw things off. Make sure you're using updated scores.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Weight discrepancy</strong> &mdash; your reading of the syllabus and your teacher's actual setup don't match. That's the first place to look.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How to Actually Improve Your Grade</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Checking your grade is useful. Using that info to <strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">change</strong> it is the whole point.</p>
<ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Focus on what carries the most weight.</strong> If you have a quiz worth 5% and a test worth 35%, don't spend equal time on both. The test matters seven times more. You can also use our <a href="/tools/percent-increase/" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">Percent Increase Calculator</a> to see how much a score jump translates to a real percentage gain.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Never let an assignment hit zero.</strong> 55% hurts. A zero hurts the same amount but leaves you with nothing. Partial credit almost always beats a zero. Submit something. Use our <a href="/tools/percent-decrease/" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">Percent Decrease Calculator</a> to see exactly how much a zero drags your average down.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Run the What-If before every major exam.</strong> Get a specific number to aim for. Students with a concrete target study more efficiently.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Adjust your target if the math doesn't work.</strong> If you need 104% to get an A, that's not going to happen. Pick a realistic goal and go after that instead.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Talk to your teacher before the exam, not after.</strong> If the What-If tells you something alarming &mdash; like needing a 97% to pass &mdash; ask about extra credit, resubmissions, or whether you understand the weights correctly. Teachers have more flexibility before grades are finalized.</li>
  <li><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Track your grade every week.</strong> The students least surprised by final grades are the ones who check weekly. Update the Weighted Grade tab every time a score comes back.</li>
</ul>
